Foot and mouth disease in Argentina
------------------------------------
Translation of an e-mail received on 14 March 2001 from Dr Eduardo Jesus
Grecco, Deputy Executive President, National Service for Agrifood Health
and Quality (SENASA), Secretariat for Agriculture, Livestock, Fisheries and
Food, Buenos Aires
Report date: 13 Mar 2001.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and from laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 12 Mar 2001.
New outbreaks:
Location: District of Rivadavia, Buenos Aires area
No. of outbreaks: 1
Description of affected population: 1 to 2 years-old, young bulls.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species / susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
bov / 2075 / 300 / -- / -- / --
Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Central Laboratory of SENASA.
Diagnosis tests used: in serum: antibodies for ELISA, in epithelium: direct
typification for ELISA.
Causal agent: virus type A.
Source of agent / origin of infection: the origin of the infection is under
investigation.
Control measures during reporting period: with regards to this situation,
the SENASA has implemented all the preventive measures recommended by the
OIE, as well as those contained in SENASA resolutions Nos. 479 and 779/99,
and shall continue to guarantee the hygiene of the products it currently
certifies. Consequently, certification shall be restricted to destinations
where this epidemiological situation represents a constraint and to any
product which may constitute a risk, as indicated in the OIE directives
relating to this disease.
Movement control inside the country, screening, vaccination.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Note the virus strain in this outbreak is not the O type involved in the
UK and elsewhere. There actually have been virus types other than the
Asian O strain involved in some of the noteworthy FMD outbreaks in the last
18 months. - Mod.PC
